Reflecting on the development of our task management system, 
I am proud of how much I've grown by bridging the gap between 
theoretical concepts and a fully functional application. Building 
the system from the initial environment setup to a standalone 
executable using PyInstaller taught me the immense value of structured, 
iterative project management. One of my most significant technical takeaways 
was integrating the Telegram API for cross-platform notifications instead of 
relying on standard local desktop alerts. Figuring out how to seamlessly sync 
the Python scheduling algorithms with the API and the HTML frontend was challenging, 
but it showed me firsthand how technical trade-offs like requiring an active internet 
connection are often necessary to create a more accessible, multi-device user experience.

Beyond the code itself, this project significantly broadened my 
understanding of computing ethics and user-centric design. 
Implementing dynamic dark and light modes wasn't just a stylistic choice; 
it was a deliberate effort to improve accessibility and reduce digital eye strain for our users. 
Similarly, designing the system to process data locally and only transmit essential reminder data via 
the API reinforced the importance of protecting user privacy. Ultimately,
this experience shifted my perspective from simply making a program run to actively
considering the real-world impact and ethical responsibilities we hold as software creators.
